'''Dominic John Hyam''' (born 20 December 1995) is a Scottish professional [[association football|footballer]] who plays for {{English football updater|BlackbuR}} club [[Wrexham A.F.C.|Wrexham]] and the [[Scotland national football team|Scotland national team]]. He is known as a reliable, robust and consistent [[centre-back]].<ref name=rovism/>

Starting his career at [[Reading F.C.|Reading]], he played on loan for [[Hemel Hempstead Town F.C.|Hemel Hempstead Town]], [[Basingstoke Town F.C.|Basingstoke Town]], [[Dagenham & Redbridge F.C.|Dagenham & Redbridge]] and [[Aldershot Town F.C.|Aldershot Town]]. At [[Coventry City F.C.|Coventry City]] he won promotion by winning the 2018 [[EFL League Two]] play-offs, and then as 2019–20 [[EFL League One]] champions. He was player of the year at Coventry in 2018–19 and at [[Blackburn Rovers]] in 2022–23.

After winning three under-19 and five under-21 Scotland caps, he debuted as a full Scotland international in [[Oslo]] in 2023.

==Club career==
===Reading===
Hyam began his career with [[Reading F.C.|Reading]] in 2008 at the age of 12, progressing through the youth system to become an integral part of the youth team that reached the [[Premier Academy League]] final in 2013.<ref name="Centre back signs contract">{{cite web|url=http://www.readingfc.co.uk/news/article/hyam-pens-pro-deal-1196626.aspx|title=Centre back signs contract|publisher=Reading F.C.|date=25 November 2013|access-date=13 February 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131202225535/http://www.readingfc.co.uk/news/article/hyam-pens-pro-deal-1196626.aspx|archive-date=2 December 2013}}</ref> Aged 17, in November 2013, he signed his first professional contract with the club on a three-year deal.<ref name="Centre back signs contract"/>

In February 2015, Hyam joined [[Conference South]] side [[Hemel Hempstead Town F.C.|Hemel Hempstead Town]] on an initial one-month loan. The loan later extended until the end of the season.<ref name="Tudors snap up Royals starlet Hyam on loan">{{cite web|url=http://www.hemeltoday.co.uk/sport/hemeltownfc/tudors-snap-up-royals-starlet-hyam-on-loan-1-6562781|title=Tudors snap up Royals starlet Hyam on loan|work=Hemel Today|date=6 February 2015|access-date=13 February 2016}}</ref> Hyam played every minute of all 14 league games he played in for Hemel. The club finished the season in ninth place.<ref name=sw/>

On 26 November 2015, Hyam joined [[2015–16 National League|National League]] (the newly re-branded name for the Conference League), [[Basingstoke Town F.C.|Basingstoke Town]] on loan until 2 January 2016. He played every minute of all five league games he played in during his six weeks there.<ref name=sw/>

On 1 February 2016, Hyam joined [[EFL League Two]], [[Dagenham & Redbridge F.C.|Dagenham & Redbridge]] on loan initially until 5 March 2016.<ref name="Hyam joins Daggers on loan">{{cite web|title=Daggers Secure Deadline Day Move|url=http://www.daggers.co.uk/news/article/daggers-secure-deadline-day-move-2932086.aspx|website=daggers.co.uk|publisher=[[Dagenham & Redbridge F.C.]]|access-date=1 February 2016|date=1 February 2016}}</ref> Staying until the season's end, Hyam started all of the 16 league games he played there.<ref name=sw/>

On 9 May 2016, Hyam was one of 15 Reading youth-team players offered a new contract by the club,<ref>{{cite web|title=Contract offers made to Academy talent|url=http://www.readingfc.co.uk/news/article/contract-offers-made-to-academy-talent-end-of-season-2015-16-3104473.aspx|publisher=Reading F.C.|access-date=9 May 2016|date=9 May 2016}}</ref> with conformation of his new deal being signed coming on 1 July 2016.<ref>{{cite web|title=15 youngsters sign new pro deals with Reading|url=http://www.readingfc.co.uk/news/article/2016-17/15-youngsters-sign-new-pro-deals-with-reading-3164112.aspx|publisher=Reading F.C.|access-date=1 July 2016|date=1 July 2016}}</ref>

In August 2016 he played in three Reading under 23 games before on 31 August, joining [[Portsmouth F.C.|Portsmouth]] on loan until 8 January 2017.<ref name="Portsmouth Loan Hyam">{{cite web|title=Hyam secures Fratton Park loan|url=http://www.readingfc.co.uk/news/article/2016-17/dom-hyam-signs-loan-deal-with-portsmouth-3284877.aspx|publisher=Reading F.C.|access-date=31 August 2016|date=31 August 2016}}</ref> However after not playing any Portsmouth first team minutes, he was featuring for Reading under 23s again by the end of November.<ref name=sw/>

On 23 March 2017, Hyam joined National League [[Aldershot Town F.C.|Aldershot Town]] on loan until the end of the season.<ref name="Aldershot loan Hyam">{{cite web|title=SHOTS SIGN ROYALS' HYAM|url=https://www.theshots.co.uk/shots-sign-royals-hyam/|website=theshots.co.uk|publisher=Aldershot Town F.C.|access-date=23 March 2017|date=23 March 2017}}</ref> He played in three league games for Aldershot.<ref name=sw/>

On 12 May 2017, Reading announced that Hyam, and nine others, would be leaving the club on the expiration of the contract at the end of June.<ref>{{cite web|title=Club offer contracts to young talent|url=http://www.readingfc.co.uk/news/article/2016-17/club-offer-contracts-to-young-talent-3714279.aspx|publisher=Reading F.C.|date=12 May 2017|access-date=16 May 2017}}</ref>

===Coventry City===
On 24 May 2017, League Two side [[Coventry City F.C.|Coventry City]] announced the signing of Hyam on a two-year contract, beginning on 1 July 2017.<ref>{{cite web|title=Coventry City: Dominic Hyam and Liam O'Brien join Sky Blues on two-year deals|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/40028086|work=BBC Sport|access-date=24 May 2017|date=24 May 2017}}</ref> He ended the season with 17 appearances. Coventry qualified for the end of season play offs by finishing sixth. Hyam played in both semi-final games winning 5–2 on aggregate over [[Notts County]]. Hyam then played on 28 May 2018 in the [[Wembley Stadium]] play off final 3–1 win over [[Exeter City]] to win promotion.<ref name=playfin>{{Cite web|url=http://www.theguardian.com/football/live/2018/may/28/coventry-city-v-exeter-city-league-two-play-off-final-live|title=Coventry promoted to League One after 3–1 play-off win over Exeter – as it happened|first=Nick|last=Ames|date=28 May 2018|work=The Guardian}}</ref>

Hyam entered into new contract discussions with Coventry at the end of the 2017–18 season.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/44317864|title=Michael Doyle: Coventry City captain triggers contract extension|date=31 May 2018|access-date=2 June 2018|work=BBC Sport}}</ref> He signed a new two-year contract in December 2019.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/50859363|title=Dominic Hyam: Coventry City defender signs new two-year deal|work=BBC Sport|date=19 December 2019}}</ref>

In Coventry's 2018–19 season they finished eighth in League One. Hyam started in 37 of his 38 league appearances that season. In 2019–20 Coventry were promoted as League One champions. Hyam started in 28 of his 29 league appearances.<ref name=sw/> He was Coventry City Player of the Year that season.<ref name="award1">{{cite news|url=https://www.coventrytelegraph.net/sport/football/football-news/winners-coventry-citys-end-season-16232168|title=The winners from the Sky Blues end of season awards|first=Andy|last=Turner|date=6 May 2019|work=Coventry Telegraph}}</ref>

In the 2020–21 and 2021–22 seasons, Coventry consolidated their position in English football's second tier by finished 16th and 12th respectively. Hyam played regularly in both seasons. In August 2022 he was sold to Blackburn in a deal that was described in the ''Coventry Telegraph'' as "a hugely unpopular sale".<ref name=covtelsal>{{Cite web|url=https://www.coventrytelegraph.net/sport/football/football-news/coventry-transfers-dom-hyam-blackburn-26523067|title=What Coventry City can expect to earn from Dom Hyam's move to Blackburn Rovers|first=Andy|last=Turner|date=21 March 2023|website=Coventry Live}}</ref> In total his time at Coventry included 170 first team league appearances.<ref name=sw/> He scored eight goals in 192 Coventry league and cup first team games.<ref name=fivethings>{{Cite web|url=https://www.rovers.co.uk/news/2022/august/29/five-things-you-might-not-know-about-dom-hyam-/|title=Five things you might not know about Dom Hyam!|date=29 August 2022|website=Blackburn Rovers FC}}</ref>

===Blackburn Rovers===
On 28 August 2022, Hyam signed for [[Blackburn Rovers F.C.|Blackburn Rovers]], aged 26, on a three-year contract.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/football/62705905|title=Dom Hyam: Blackburn Rovers sign Coventry City defender for undisclosed fee|date=29 August 2022|work=BBC Sport}}</ref> It was reported that his undisclosed fee was "for a knock-down £1.5million." The fee was later revealed as "closer to £2.5m" plus "add-ons that could eventually add up to close to £3m."<ref name=covtelsal/>

Hyam scored his first Blackburn goal on 13 September winning 2–0 versus [[Watford F.C.|Watford]].<ref>{{cite news |title=Blackburn 2–0 Watford |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/62803562 |access-date=14 September 2022 |publisher=BBC Sport |date=13 September 2022}}</ref> He started 37 Blackburn league games that season. Blackburn finished the season seventh, on goal difference one place below [[Sunderland AFC|Sunderland]] in the sixth place play off spot.{{citation needed|date=July 2025}} Blackburn eliminated top division Leicester City en route to the [[FA Cup]] quarter-finals.<ref name=sw/> Hyam was Rovers Player of the Year that season.<ref name=brmvp/>

In [[2023–24 Blackburn Rovers F.C. season|2023–24]] Hyam started 35 league games.<ref name=sw/> Blackburn finished the season in 19th place. They reached the FA Cup fifth round in which they lost to top division [[Newcastle United]] on penalties. [[Sammie Szmodics]] and Hyam were the Rovers players to have penalties saved.<ref name=blanewesp>{{Cite web|url=https://www.espn.com/soccer/commentary/_/gameId/698127|title=Newcastle 1–1 Blackburn (Feb 27, 2024) Commentary|website=ESPN}}</ref>

Hyam played every minute of Blackburn's 2024–25 league campaign.<ref name=leag25>{{Cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=xX9U7_h9qg8|title=Dom Hyam didn't miss a league minute in 2024/25!|date=19 May 2025|via=YouTube}}</ref> Blackburn ended the season seventh in the league after a 1–1 draw against [[Sheffield United]] in the last game of the season, which denied Rovers the sixth place play-off spot.<ref name=shefbla>{{Cite web|url=https://www.espn.in/football/match/_/gameId/708168/blackburn-rovers-sheffield-united|title=Sheffield Utd 1–1 Blackburn (3 May, 2025) Final Score|website=ESPN}}</ref>

===Wrexham===
On 1 September 2025, Hyam signed a two-year contract with [[EFL Championship]] club [[Wrexham A.F.C.|Wrexham]].<ref>{{cite web |last1=Pritchard |first1=Dafydd |title=Wrexham show intent with Sheaf, Hyam and Kabore signings |url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/football/articles/c79l2g4lv29o |publisher=BBC Sport |access-date=1 September 2025 |date=1 September 2025}}</ref> On 9 January 2026, he scored his first goal for the club in their third round [[2025–26 FA Cup|FA Cup]] penalty shoot-out victory over [[Nottingham Forest F.C.|Nottingham Forest]].<ref>{{Cite web|title=Wrexham 3–3 Nottm Forest (Jan 9, 2026) Game Analysis|url=https://www.espn.com/soccer/report/_/gameId/762493|access-date=2026-03-08|website=ESPN|language=en}}</ref>

==International career==
Hyam was called up to represent [[Scotland national under-19 football team|Scotland under-19]] while at Reading.<ref name=Herald2014/> On 24 May 2014, he debuted internationally with the under-19s, in a 0–0 draw with Ukraine in Burton on Trent. Hyam lined up with fellow centre-backs, [[John Souttar]] and [[Scott McKenna]].<ref name=scoukr19>{{Cite web|url=https://www.scottishfa.co.uk/international-matches/?mid=141001|title=International Matches|website=www.scottishfa.co.uk}}</ref> Scottish captain [[Adam King (footballer)|Adam King]] missed a second half penalty.<ref name=scoukrsco>{{Cite web|url=https://www.scotsman.com/sport/football/ukraine-u-19-0-0-scotland-u-19-scots-on-the-spot-1-3422050|title="Ukraine U-19 0–0 Scotland U-19: Scots on the spot"|work=scotsman.com|date=24 May 2014}}</ref> Hyam then played two days later at the same venue against host nation England in a 2–1 defeat for Scotland.<ref name=scoeng19>{{Cite web|url=https://www.scottishfa.co.uk/international-matches/?mid=141002|title=International Matches|website=www.scottishfa.co.uk}}</ref> Hyam's third and last under 19 cap was three days later in the same competition, this time in [[Walsall]]. Scotland lost 1–0 to Montenegro.<ref name=scomon>{{Cite web|url=https://www.scottishfa.co.uk/international-matches/?mid=141004|title=International Matches|website=www.scottishfa.co.uk}}</ref>

[[File:Украина U-21 - Шотландия U-21 4-0. 6 сентября 2016 года — 708159.jpg|right|thumb|Hyam (number 13) and the under 21s pre-match in Ukraine.]]
Hyam's [[Scotland national under-21 football team|under-21]] debut was on 18 November 2014, drawing 1–1 in Switzerland.<ref name=swisco21>{{Cite web|url=https://www.scottishfa.co.uk/international-matches/?mid=147876|title=International Matches|website=www.scottishfa.co.uk}}</ref><ref name=sfa>{{SFA Profile|id=348577}}</ref><ref name = stvcall/> After a 2–1 away win over Hungary in March 2015 ([[Lawrence Shankland]] scored both Scots goals),<ref name=hunsco21>{{Cite web|url=https://www.scottishfa.co.uk/international-matches/?mid=150910|title=International Matches|website=www.scottishfa.co.uk}}</ref> Hyam then played in three European Championship qualifiers. These were 2015 home draws with Iceland (0–0)<ref name=scoice21>{{Cite web|url=https://www.scottishfa.co.uk/international-matches/?mid=150914|title=International Matches|website=www.scottishfa.co.uk}}</ref> and Ukraine (2–2)<ref name=scoukr21>{{Cite web|url=https://www.scottishfa.co.uk/international-matches/?mid=150915|title=International Matches|website=www.scottishfa.co.uk}}</ref> before losing in Ukraine 4–0 in September 2016.<ref name=ukrsco21>{{Cite web|url=https://www.scottishfa.co.uk/international-matches/?mid=150919|title=International Matches|website=www.scottishfa.co.uk}}</ref>

In March 2023, Hyam said of playing for Scotland, "That would mean the world to me."<ref name=foosco>{{Cite web|url=https://www.footballscotland.co.uk/spfl/other-football/who-dominic-hyam-new-scotland-26522715|title=New Scotland defender Dominic Hyam profiled as Blackburn star earns call up|first=Aidan|last=Scott|date=21 March 2023|website=Football Scotland}}</ref> Later that month Hyam was added to the [[Scotland national football team|Scotland]] senior squad for the first time. He replaced the injured [[Jack Hendry (footballer, born 1995)|Jack Hendry]].<ref name = stvcall>{{cite web |url=https://news.stv.tv/sport/blackburn-rovers-defender-dom-hyam-earns-first-call-to-scotland-squad |title=Blackburn Rovers defender Dom Hyam earns first call to Scotland squad |first=Andy |last=Coyle |website=STV News |date=21 March 2023 |accessdate=21 March 2023}}</ref>

Aged 27, Hyam made his full international debut on 17 June 2023 versus [[Norway national football team|Norway]] in [[Oslo]]. He came on as a substitute for [[John McGinn]] in the 91st minute of a 2–1 win for Scotland.<ref name=uefnorsco>{{Cite web|url=https://www.uefa.com/european-qualifiers/match/2036336--norway-vs-scotland/|title=History: Norway-Scotland &#124; European Qualifiers 2024|website=UEFA.com}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.skysports.com/football/news/11095/12904481/steve-clarke-hails-scotland-character-after-norway-comeback-win-andrew-robertson-we-have-to-qualify-for-euro-2024-now |title=Steve Clarke hails Scotland character after Norway comeback win |website=Sky Sports |date=17 June 2023 |accessdate=17 June 2023}}</ref>

On 31 March 2026, nearly 3 years after his first cap, Hyam earned his second cap and first start for Scotland in a 0–1 friendly loss to the [[Ivory Coast national football team|Ivory Coast]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/live/cew75ny45v9t#Line-ups |title=International Friendly LIVE: Scotland vs Ivory Coast |website=BBC Sport |date=31 March 2026 |accessdate=1 April 2026}}</ref>

==Style of play==
When signing Hyam, Blackburn Rovers Director of Football, Gregg Broughton, commented on "Hyam's passing, one-versus-one defensive duel and leadership abilities".<ref name=grill>{{Cite web|url=https://sportgrill.co.uk/2022/08/28/blackburn-rovers-sign-dominic-hyam-from-coventry-city/|title=Blackburn Rovers Sign Dominic Hyam From Coventry City|first=James|last=Gregory|date=28 August 2022|website=Sport Grill}}</ref>

Hyam was described on the Blackburn Rovers website in April 2025 as, "Reliable and robust". Manager [[Valerien Ismael]] added, "He's solid, he's played every game and stands up even when he gets injured, so it's good to have that reliability. He has that consistency to play and a clear profile for a centre-back in being strong in the duels, good on the ball, has that experience and is vocal."<ref name=rovism>{{Cite web|url=https://www.rovers.co.uk/news/2025/april/08/hyam-fits-the-bill--says-ismael/|title=Hyam fits the bill, says Ismael|date=8 April 2025|website=Blackburn Rovers FC}}</ref>

Hyam himself commented in May 2025, "I've had a bit of luck with injuries. I know they are part of the game and I'll get injuries in the future, but availability and consistency is what I've always based my game on. You have to take care of your body and that's something I've stepped up with and taken a lot more seriously in 2024–25."<ref name=rovershap>{{Cite web|url=https://www.rovers.co.uk/news/2025/may/21/hyam-happy-with-availability-and-consistency/|title=Hyam happy with availability and consistency|date=21 May 2025|website=Blackburn Rovers FC}}</ref>

==Personal life==
In May 2014, ''[[The Herald (Glasgow)|The Herald]]'' reported Hyam as stating, "My dad was in the [[Royal Air Force|RAF]] from the age of 16 and used to be based at [[Leuchars]] in [[Fife]]. My mum was pregnant with me at the time and that's where I was born. He was only there for between six months and a year before we moved back down south. I've got more Scottish than English in me because my dad's mum is from Dundee originally and mum's dad is from Glasgow."<ref name=Herald2014>{{cite news|url=http://www.heraldscotland.com/sport/13162804.Hyam_is_not_for_heading_south/|title=Hyam is not for heading south|work=Herald Scotland|date=29 May 2014|access-date=13 February 2016}}</ref><ref name=thenat23>{{Cite web|url=https://www.thenational.scot/sport/23402080.dominic-hyam-blackburn-defender-keen-scotland-cap/|title=Who is Dominic Hyam? The Blackburn defender keen for Scotland cap|date=21 March 2023|website=The National}}</ref> Hyam cites his 'Scotland-daft dad' as his main influence.<ref name=rec23>{{Cite web|url=https://www.dailyrecord.co.uk/sport/football/who-dominic-hyam-scotland-cap-29510918|title=Everything to know about Dominic Hyam as he sees Scotland dream come true|first=Robbie|last=Copeland|date=21 March 2023|website=Daily Record}}</ref>

